The method used in this study combines synthetic indices that provide a measure of vulnerability in different aspects that are defined between the dimensions of exposure, sensitivity, adaptive capacity, and their association to climatic hazards (Table 1
                            and Fig. 2
                           ). Using SisVuClima, information is statistically analyzed for each municipality and a MVI is calculated in relation to climate change from both Representative Concentration Pathways (RCPs) 4.5 and 8.5 (see later). Data selection was based on i) data availability, ii) the conceptual framework established by previous research and developed by Fiocruz (Barata et al., 2015, Confalonieri et al., 2015, 2016), and iii) scientific literature on the quantification and evaluation of vulnerability (Adger, 2004; Brooks et al., 2005; SabelliScale Counts, 2011; Moss et al., 2001; Sabelli, 2011).

All the procedures were performed using the SisVuClima software. A scale for all indices was used as a measure of vulnerability, with values standardized to be between 0 and 1 using the formula: δ = (X – Xmin
                           ) / (Xmax

                           – 
                           Xmin
                           ), where δ is the standardized value, X is the original variable, and Xmin and Xmax are the lowest and the highest values of the variable, respectively. The values of the indices were categorized as follows: 0 (minimum), 0.001–0.250 (low), 0.251 –0.500 (moderate), 0.501–0.750 (high), 0.751–0.999 (very high), and 1 (maximum).
